		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../atem.png" alt="ATEM 2006 SI"></a><br><code>atem2006s/paper04</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">ATEM 2006 SI</a> paper:</span><br><i>Learning Context-Free Grammar Rules from a Set of Program</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/AlpanaDubey.html">Alpana Dubey</a>, <a href="../profile/PankajJalote.html">Pankaj Jalote</a>, <a href="../profile/ShubhaniAggarwal.html">Shubhani Aggarwal</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1049/iet-sen:20070061">10.1049/iet-sen:20070061</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> The core task is inferring missing context-free grammar rules (grammar completion) from program samples and an approximate grammar.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2a.html"><span class="tagL">T2A: Lifecycle</span></a><ul><li> It targets reverse engineering of dialect grammars when documentation/manuals are missing, i.e., recovery of language definitions.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagL">T5E: Empirical Evaluation</span></a><ul><li> The approach is experimentally verified on multiple programming languages to demonstrate feasibility and effectiveness.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> The inferred artefacts are CFG rules, i.e., meta-language objects used to define and generate parsers.
</li></ul></li></ul>
		<clear/>
		<footer/>
	</body>
</html>
